Scientists say the disease has an incubation period of 10 years or more.
Kiril Kirov, director of the government's veterinary service, told the newspaper 168 hours that "the import and the usage of the Dutch test is a violation of EU requirements".
In June 2004 the country switched to a Dutch test not yet recognised by the commission's veterinary control service.
The cow was born in Shikaoi, north Japan's Hokkaido region, in October 2000, and was checked for mad cow disease after it died, the ministry said.